post_text:
Today's Speechie Story Teller is WCHS alum, Will Crouch. Will was a four year member of the WCHS Speech Team. Will competed in Prose Reading, Humorous Duet Acting, and Original Comedy. Will was an IHSA State Qualifier his junior and senior years in both Humorous Duet Acting and Original Comedy. His senior year, he, along with duet partner, Ava Stovall, was a State Finalist in Humorous Duet Acting. Will says the best part of being on the speech team is the friends you make along the way and the laughs you share. His favorite speech memory was competing with partner, Ava. They really are a dynamic duo! Will is a rising sophomore at Augustana College.

The story Will is sharing with you today is I Love You Stinky Face by Lisa McCourt.

post_text: Caden Davidson has been named a finalist in the National Merit Scholarship Program of 2020. Over 1.5 million juniors entered and 15,000 advanced as semi-finalists. By the conclusion of the 2020 competition, 7,600 were selected to receive National Merit Scholarships. Finalists demonstrate the strongest combination of academic skills and achievements, extracurricular accomplishments, and potential for success in rigorous college studies. This is an exceptional academic achievement! Congratulations, Caden! #wchspantherpride

Today's Story Time with the WCHS Speechies features junior, Helen Ward. Helen has been on the WCHS Speech Team for three years. During that time, she has competed in Informative Speaking, Oratorical Declamation, and Radio Speaking. Helen's favorite part of being on the speech team is meeting and becoming friends with students from all over the state. Her favorite memory happened when WCHS hosted the IHSA Sectional Tournament this past February. Before awards, two boys from opposing teams started a crazy, dramatic game of Rock Paper Scissors on the West Gym floor. Before long, everyone in the packed gym had chosen a side and was rooting for their player to win. It was so much fun!

Today, Helen will be reading the story, Puppies! Puppies! Puppies!, by Susan Meyers. https://bit.ly/2LBi55C #wchspantherpride

Congratulations to seniors, William Atchison, Addie Beebe, and Isaiah Rodriguez for receiving National Scholastic Medals! #wchspantherpride

More than 110,000 students submitted nearly 320,000 works of art and writing to the 2020 Scholastic Awards. Only 3,000 works received a National Medal, which places these WCHS students within the top 1% of all submissions!

The ceremony in New York was canceled, but there will be a Virtual Celebration that will be inclusive of both Silver and Gold Medal Recipients. This live event will be on June 4, at 6:00 pm EDT (5:00 pm CDT).

Scholastic has prepared a virtual exhibition of the student's work and an online gallery. Links for each student below.
Atchison https://bit.ly/2WyDiCn
Beebe https://bit.ly/2zclepR
Rodriguez https://bit.ly/2WzKCO6

IMPORTANT INFORMATION: As you know, Coronavirus (COVID-19) has been a source of growing public concern. We were informed late this afternoon by the Governor of Illinois that all public and private schools in Illinois will be closed starting Tuesday, March 17.

Students will not be in attendance starting this Monday, March 16, but teachers will report to school for an Institute Day.

We are working to finalize decisions about E-Learning, and we will send more information on Monday so students can begin at-home E-Learning on Tuesday, March 17.

The spring play will be held this evening with a limit of 200 tickets sold. ALL activities for Saturday and Sunday are cancelled or postponed.

We recognize that closing school will have a significant impact on everyone, and we appreciate your patience during this unprecedented time. Superintendent, Dr. Kyle Freeman

It is the end of a construction era at the high school. The renovation of the old band room is complete, and it is time to bid farewell to the large dumpster in the circle drive. With this change, we evaluated the use of the circle drive and the drop off/pick up procedure.

Effective Tuesday, February 25, the circle drive will be open 8:30 a.m. ‚Äì 2:30 p.m., and the current drop off/pick up procedure will continue as it is today. Note: If you are parked in the circle drive when it closes at 2:30 p.m., you will not be permitted to leave until 3:15 p.m. This is for the safety of students walking in the area during peak times.

post_text:
Today, culinary arts students participated in the WCHS Cupcake Battle with a Valentine‚Äôs Day theme.

Ms. McLauchlan said, ‚ÄúOur focus this week was on presentation, 'You Eat With Your Eyes First'. The students were to come up with a cupcake creation that displayed that objective. The students worked with their lab group and had to do multiple steps. This included everything from planning, creating a cupcake vision, creating a grocery list that stayed within a specific budget, and then the students needed to come up with a creative display name and plate design. The cupcakes were judged by a panel of 4 'celebrity' judges per class period. The judges critiqued the cupcakes on display presentation, flavor/texture of frosting, flavor/texture of cupcake, and overall creativity."

Check out the creations from our talented students. http://bit.ly/31XEZLP

Read more about the opportunity to have a once in a lifetime custom trip experience. WCHS students, parents, faculty or staff are invited to attend. Visit Germany, Austria, Italy, and Switzerland, June 15-23, 2021 - Art and History Focus. Learn more about the itinerary, fees, and how to sign up on our website. Deadlines are coming soon! http://bit.ly/2SmhBEX

‚ÄúWe will have an up close look at the spectacular art and history around this section of Europe. We are going to take a gondola ride in Venice and learn all about the Venetian culture. We are also going to take a ride up to Mt. Pilatus and a toboggan ride down the Swiss alps. We are also going to see, respectfully, the concentration camp Dachau. Get ready to experience local food and be mesmerized by local art, architecture and culture. This is truly a once in a lifetime experience. This trip has been custom designed to make the most of the time we are there. I can't wait to have you come along on this adventure!‚Äù Ms. Kuchan

WCHS participated in the Mid-Central Region of The Scholastic Art Show in Springfield. This was a juried and judged show, and the WCHS art department did exceedingly well this year.

There are only 5 American Vision Awards given each year, and our students received 3 out of these 5 awards! We received 18 Gold Keys, Silver Keys, and Honorable Mention awards, and a gold and silver art portfolio. Gold Key recipients had digital images of their work sent to New York City to be juried for the National Scholastics Art Show in March and will attend an honors art making day in February. Congratulations everyone! #wchspantherpride

So many of our students give of their time to serve others, and we have a couple of recent examples to share. Keep it up, Panthers! #wchspantherpride

National Honor Society students hosted a blood drive on November 8. Students and staff together donated 106 units! This annual event helps so many people in the area.

On November 11, the IMPACT group visited Illinois Cancer Care to deliver handmade blankets that were made in partnership with the Washington Central 6th grade class. Our students brought a lot of cheer when visiting with people, and the blankets were welcome on such a cold day.

post_text:
We are thankful that so many parents, students, and community members came to see the new Frances Whittaker Center for Musical Arts wing. The opening ceremony included special guests Marilyn Whittaker and Dick Whittaker, who are the niece and nephew of Frances Whittaker.

We heard from Superintendent Dr. Kyle Freeman and Board of Education President, Jennifer Essig, along with our band and choir directors. We appreciate that the band and choir students came out on Homecoming weekend to perform. Their commitment to our music programs shines through, and it was a special day to dedicate their new music home at the school.

Fun Facts: The old choir room was 1,564 square feet and the new room is 2,218. The old band room was 2,203 square feet and the new room is 4,208. The new addition also offers instrument and file storage, practice rooms, and two new academic classrooms on the second floor.

post_text:
For the last 29 years, the After Midnight Post-Prom Event has provided a safe environment for students to celebrate. We are seeking volunteers that would be willing to chair the event and make it the best 30th year! Seasoned volunteers are available to help guide those taking over and the new committee chair(s) will have the support of students, parents, and WCHS staff who serve as committee members.

If you are interested in the committee chair position, please contact Lindsay Winter, WCHS Dean of Students & Activity Director, at (309) 444-5521 or lmwinter@wacohi.net.

We are fortunate that faithful parent volunteers have chaired the committee well past their children graduating from WCHS, but it is time to pass the baton to the next generation of parents. Thank you for considering this volunteer role and the continuation of the After Midnight Post-Prom event.

Today, we remember.

Many of our students participated in Washington's annual 9/11 Memorial Ceremony on Sunday. The WCHS cheerleaders, drumline, and several sports teams and coaches led participants to the ceremony with a walk through the park. We are proud that our students continue this tradition. We are also thankful for our local first responders and their commitment to protecting our school and city.

post_text: Hey Panther Fans! Tonight is the first home football game, and the stadium looks a little different since last fall. The biggest change is moving the home side bleachers to the west side (old visitor‚Äôs side). The home side bleachers now seat around 2,500 people! See the picture below to become familiar with where everything is--home bleachers, ticket booths, ADA entrances, parking, and closed areas. For those planning to sit on the home side and require an ADA entrance, the most direct access is through the parking lot located on Wilmor Road (behind the new home side bleachers). We hope you can attend and look forward to a great night! #wchspantherpride
